When you create a new `ImGuiContext`, by default, an INI file called "imgui.ini" is loaded and used to store persistent settings and preferences, including window positions and sizes.

To prevent your ImGui window from resetting to the previous location and size, you can either:

1. Disable INI file loading by passing a `nullptr` value instead of a filename as the `ini_filename` parameter of `ImGui::CreateContext()`. This will prevent ImGui from attempting to load any INI files and will prevent it from overwriting window positions and sizes.

```c++
ImGui::CreateContext(nullptr);
```

2. If you're using an INI file to store your settings, make sure to call `ImGui::SaveIniSettingsToDisk()` after making any changes to the window location or size. `SaveIniSettingsToDisk()` writes the current state of the ImGui context to the INI file. If you don't call this function, any changes you make to window positions and sizes will be lost the next time the application runs.

```c++
while (!glfwWindowShouldClose(window)) {
    // ...

    // Save ImGui settings to INI file
    ImGui::SaveIniSettingsToDisk("imgui.ini");
}
```

Either approach should prevent ImGui from resetting your window position and size. Let me know if this answers your question or if you have any further questions or concerns.

To stick buttons to the bottom line of an ImGui window, you can make use of the `ImGui::GetWindowDrawList()` and `ImGui::GetWindowPos()` functions to calculate the position of the bottom edge of the window.

Here's an example of how you can create a button at the bottom of an ImGui window:

```c++
bool showButton = true;
while (!glfwWindowShouldClose(window)) {
    ImGui::Begin("My Window");

    // ...

    // Get the window position and size
    ImVec2 windowPos = ImGui::GetWindowPos();
    ImVec2 windowSize = ImGui::GetWindowSize();

    // Calculate the position of the button
    ImVec2 buttonPos(windowPos.x + windowSize.x / 2, windowPos.y + windowSize.y - 40);

    // Display the button
    if (showButton) {
        if (ImGui::Button("My Button", ImVec2(100, 30))) {
            // ...
        }
    }

    // ...

    ImGui::End();
}
```

This code uses `ImGui::GetWindowPos()` and `ImGui::GetWindowSize()` to retrieve the position and size of the current window. It then subtracts the height of the button (30 pixels in this case) from the window height and adds it to the window's Y coordinate. This gives us the Y coordinate of the button's bottom edge.

The `ImGui::Button()` function is then called with the calculated position to display the button at the bottom of the window.

